00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:40,080
 of an imperial villa, a Hellenistic town, and military camp or kestrum. Sixteen towers on the outer walls

190
00:20:40,080 --> 00:20:46,560
 give the impression of a fortress. The outer walls of the palace are for the most part still well preserved.

191
00:20:46,560 --> 00:20:53,440
 The palace had three land entrances and its main streets merged in the peristyle. The center of the palace,

192
00:20:53,440 --> 00:21:00,480
 an open space lined with arched pillars. Diocletian's mausoleum is a monumental octagonal building with

193
00:21:00,480 --> 00:21:06,960
 reliefs depicting the emperor Diocletian and his wife Prisca. The palace was built using stone from the

194
00:21:06,960 --> 00:21:12,800
 on the island of Brach and from the nearby town of Strogir. Marble columns were brought from Egyptian

195
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:19,840
 temples and the tiled floors were of Greek marble. The entire historical complex of Split with the palace

196
00:21:19,840 --> 00:21:25,840
 of Diocletian was added to the UNESCO list of world heritage sites in 1979.

197
00:21:28,720 --> 00:21:35,040
 The baptistry of St. John, located in the peristyle in the center of the impressive Diocletian's palace,

198
00:21:35,040 --> 00:21:41,280
 in the heart of Split, was once the Temple of Asclepius. By the edicts of Milan of the Roman Emperor

199
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:46,720
 Constantine the Great, persecution of Christians ceased and many temples were converted into churches.

200
00:21:46,720 --> 00:21:54,240
 Thus, the Temple of Asclepius became a baptistry dedicated to St. John the Baptist. Its baptismal font is

201
00:21:54,240 --> 00:21:59,920
 decorated with the Croatian interlace pleter and a relief depicting a Croatian ruler on his throne.

202
00:21:59,920 --> 00:22:10,080
 Ante Starcevic was born in 1823 in Ziznik, near Gospic. While still in school, he joined the Illyrian

203
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:16,640
 movement. As an expert in Croatian linguistic heritage, he prepared the first edition of the Istrian contract

204
00:22:16,640 --> 00:22:22,080
 for print, together with the Latin alphabet transcript of this glagolitic legal document.

205
00:22:22,640 --> 00:22:28,800
 He objected to the language concepts championed by Vuk Karadzic and rejected outright the Viennese

206
00:22:28,800 --> 00:22:36,160
 Literary Agreement of 1850. As chief notary of the Rijeka County, he wrote the four petitions of Rijeka

207
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:41,520
 County, which are considered the basis of the political program of the Croatian Party of Rights he

208
00:22:41,520 --> 00:22:48,720
 established in 1861 with Eugen Kvaternik and Peter Vrdoljak. He participated in the work of the Croatian

209
00:22:48,720 --> 00:22:54,000
 parliaments and thereby represented the point of view of the Croatian state law, the integrity of the

210
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:58,800
 Croatian lands, and the right of the Croatian people to self-determination, and considered

211
00:22:58,800 --> 00:23:06,000
 pan-slavic and Yugoslav ideas fatal to the Croatian people. Because of inter-party conflicts in 1895,

212
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:12,160
 he founded the pure party of rights. Through his writings and political work he laid the foundations

213
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:18,480
 of the modern independent Croatian state and was acclaimed as the father of the nation within his lifetime.

214
00:23:20,720 --> 00:23:29,120
 Tomislav was a Croatian ruler who reigned approximately from 910 to 928. His origin is unknown, but he was

215
00:23:29,120 --> 00:23:35,760
 likely to have come from the Serpimirović dynasty. Thomas, the archdeacon, noted that Tomislav was a prince,

216
00:23:35,760 --> 00:23:42,080
 duk, in 914, which is the only reliable source of information about him. From two letters written

217
00:23:42,080 --> 00:23:48,800
 by Pope John X and Leo VI, it has been concluded that Tomislav was the first Croatian ruler to use

218
00:23:48,800 --> 00:23:55,040
 the title of king and control the Dalmatian towns and islands, then nominally under Byzantium rule.

219
00:23:55,040 --> 00:24:01,840
 In the 20th century, Franjo Raczki and Ivan Kukuljevic-Saksinski wrote about Tomislav as the first

220
00:24:01,840 --> 00:24:09,200
 Croatian king, crowned in 925 on the Dubno field, following a victory of the Hungarians and Bulgarians.

221
00:24:09,200 --> 00:24:18,640
 The construction of the Zagreb cathedral began in 1102, shortly after Hungarian king Ladislaus

222
00:24:18,640 --> 00:24:25,520
 founded the Zagreb diocese. It was built in the Romanesque style in 1217, but was completely destroyed

223
00:24:25,520 --> 00:24:31,520
 by the Tatars. Bishop Timothy restored it in the Gothic style in the late 13th century.

224
00:24:31,520 --> 00:24:37,040
 Restoration continued in the 14th and 15th centuries, followed by fortification walls

225
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:43,680
 and towers built in the 16th century. A Renaissance bell tower was added in the 17th century, giving

226
00:24:43,680 --> 00:24:50,320
 the cathedral its final appearance. The cathedral was again destroyed in the great earthquake of 1880,

227
00:24:50,320 --> 00:24:57,280
 after which the architect, Hermann Bollet, restored it in the neo-Gothic style. All the important work

228
00:24:57,280 --> 00:25:04,960
 was completed by 1885 and two years later, two new towers gave a new look to the Zagreb cathedral.

229
00:25:04,960 --> 00:25:12,080
 It holds the remains of three great Croats, Zrinski, Frankopan and Kvaternik, as well as three archbishops

230
00:25:12,080 --> 00:25:17,760
 and cardinals of Zagreb all of whom made their marks on the history of the Croatian church in the late

231
00:25:17,760 --> 00:25:29,440
 20th century: Stepinac, Šeper and Kukaric. The Zagreb cathedral is the largest Croatian sacral building.

